%S A389506 2,14,194,2282,30002,510470,9699634,223092806,6469693154
%N A389506 Smallest even number which cannot be written as the difference of two numbers which are less than and relatively prime to (the primorial) p(n)#.
%C A389506 Based on but not identical to Erdős Problem 854 (see link).
%H A389506 Thomas Bloom, <a href="https://www.erdosproblems.com/854">Problem 854</a>, Erdős Problems.
%e A389506 For n=2, a(2)=2 since the only numbers (bounded by 6) relative prime with p(2)# = 3# = 6 are 1 and 5, and 2 is not the difference of them.
%e A389506 For n=3, a(3)=14, since the numbers relatively prime to and bounded by p(3)# = 30 are in the set [1, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19, 23, 29]. Now 19-17=2, 17-13=4, 23-17=6, 19-11=8, 29-19=10 and 29-17=12, but no two elements differ by 14 (nor 20, 24 or 26).
%o A389506 (SageMath)
%o A389506 def a(n):
%o A389506     N=prod(Primes()[0:n]);
%o A389506     R=[a for a in range(1, N) if gcd(N, a)==1];
%o A389506     D=[j-i for (i,j) in Combinations(R,2)];
%o A389506     return min([i for i in range(2, N, 2) if i not in D]);
%o A389506 (PARI) a(n) = my(P=vecprod(primes(n)), v=select(x->(gcd(x, P)==1), [1..P]), list=List(), vs=[]); for (i=1, #v, for (j=i+1, #v, my(x=v[j]-v[i]); if (!vecsearch(vs, x), listput(list, x); vs = vecsort(list)););); my(s=Set(list)); for (k=1, vecmax(v), if (!setsearch(s, 2*k), return(2*k));); \\ _Michel Marcus_, Oct 09 2025
